      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Photo of Whitman, Frisking a Black Man</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>William R Leben letter says July 11 photo of Gov Christine Todd Whitman frisking black man during patrol with New Jersey state troopers in 1996 belies findings of recent New York Times poll that 58 percent of whites believe blacks have same chance of getting ahead in current society as they do</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>According to a nationwide poll by The New York Times (front page, July 11), 58 percent of whites believe that blacks have the same chance of getting ahead in today's society as whites.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>According to a nationwide poll by The New York Times (front page, July 11), 58 percent of whites believe that blacks have the same chance of getting ahead in today's society as whites.</p>
        <p>I hope that some of these 58 percent saw Gov. Christine Todd Whitman of New Jersey, in a baseball cap, dungarees and black gloves,  frisking a black man in a 1996 posed photo that you published on the July 11 front page.</p>
        <p>One wonders how many whites think they have the same chance of being frisked under similar circumstances.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM R. LEBEN  Oakland, Calif., July 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
